Famous Dominican impresario is in criminal court hearing today

SANTO DOMINGO. - The National District Appellate Court?s 2nd Penal 
Chamber is now hearing the appeal on a lower court?s ruling that placed 
restrictive measures against the impresario George Nader, accused of 
conspiracy to burgle the apartment owned by the Spanish businessman Jose 
Carlos Berganti?os.

In the case heard by judge Ramon H. Gonz?lez the Spaniard?s lawyers say 
Nader sent his driver Boraldino de los Santos in his vehicle to break 
into Berganti?os? apartment where a painting valued at some US$250,000 
was stolen, as well as other properties. Berganti?os lives in an 
apartment located in the center of town.

Berganti?o?s lawyer Vinicio Castillo said First Instance court judge 
Natividad de los Santos was mistaken in her ruling, because she 
should?ve also set bond for Nader at RD$500,000, the same amount as his 
driver.

While Nader?s attorney, Carlos Balc?cer, said the motion is unsuitable 
and that two accusations are debated in the case; one against Nader and 
another against Berganti?os. He said that though the two took part in 
the transaction of a building,

Berganti?os in fact wants to morally damage Nader.

He blamed Berganti?os of falsifying company documents and of refusing to 
have his handwriting verified for forgery.

Berganti?os says he was prevented from entering his own apartment and 
had to get his lawyers to go before the Justice Ministry in order to be 
able to enter his residence.

Nader?s lawyers say this version is "a lie."

